    "metadata": {
        "title": "Stockpile of personal protective equipment in hospital settings: Preparedness for influenza pandemics",
        "authors": [
            {
                "first": "Mayuko",
                "middle": [],
                "last": "Hashikura",
                "suffix": "",
                "email": "mayuko1201@hotmail.com",
                "affiliation": {}
            },
            {
                "first": "Junko",
                "middle": [],
                "last": "Kizu",
                "suffix": "",
                "email": null,
                "affiliation": {}
            }
        ]
    },
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "A MEDLINE search was performed through PubMed for January 1950 to October 2008, using the search terms \u201cProtective Devices [MeSH Terms]\u201d and \u201cDisease Outbreak [MeSH Terms].\u201d Another MEDLINE search was performed using \u201cSevere Acute Respiratory Syndrome [MeSH Terms]\u201d and \u201cEpidemiologic Measurements [MeSH Terms].\u201d In addition, we searched reports and guidelines published by various organizations, such as the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare of Japan, the World Health Organization (WHO), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), and the US Department of Labor.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Data search ::: Methods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Based on the above data, we extracted various factors, such as the influenza pandemic period, the risk classification by the HCW type, and the type and number of PPE required for HCWs per day to calculate the stockpile of PPE in hospital settings.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Data extraction ::: Methods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "We first obtained the average number of HCWs in hospital settings from the database of the Ministry of Health, Labor, and Welfare of Japan. We then developed a PPE calculation system, which can calculate the number of PPE from only the location and scale of the hospital. In this system, the stockpile of PPE is calculated by multiplying (1) the average number of HCWs determined automatically by the location and scale of the hospital, (2) the number of PPE sets required for HCWs per day, and (3) the length of the pandemic period.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "PPE calculation system ::: Methods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "As an example, the stockpile of PPE required for a sample hospital with 300 beds in Tokyo is shown using this PPE calculation system. The expenditure for PPE was calculated by multiplying the total stockpile of PPE by the average cost of PPE.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "PPE calculation system ::: Methods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "According to the search results by MEDLINE, there were 121 papers for \u201cProtective Devices [MeSH Terms]\u201d and \u201cDisease Outbreak [MeSH Terms]\u201d and 267 papers for \u201cSevere Acute Respiratory Syndrome [MeSH Terms]\u201d and \u201cEpidemiologic Measurements [MeSH Terms].\u201d In addition, we obtained influenza guidelines from 30 nations and SARS reports.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Data search ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Based on the data obtained during the SARS epidemic in 2003, we calculated the pandemic period, assuming that it started from the day that the first patient was detected to the last day when a SARS-free declaration was issued by the country. As a result, the average duration was 122 days. The average was taken from the countries shown in Table 1\n, which included more than 100 patients. China was excluded because of the unhelpful actions of the government, such as concealment at the beginning of the SARS pandemic.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Influenza pandemic period ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 340,
                    "end": 347,
                    "mention": "Table 1",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "However, the pandemic periods in each region may be shorter than 122 days, which is the national average. According to the US Department of Labor,5 the pandemic period in each region is considered to be 12 weeks at maximum. In addition, the majority of guidelines of the countries that are introduced on WHO Web site6 assume that the pandemic lasts 6 to 8 weeks (Table 2\n). The Ministry of Health, Labor, and Welfare of Japan also supposes that a pandemic will last 8 weeks4; therefore, a stockpile of PPE should be prepared to cover at least 8 weeks, although influenza pandemics could last longer with 2 or more waves.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 146,
                    "end": 147,
                    "mention": "5",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF18"
                },
                {
                    "start": 316,
                    "end": 317,
                    "mention": "6",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF19"
                },
                {
                    "start": 473,
                    "end": 474,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF17"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Influenza pandemic period ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 363,
                    "end": 370,
                    "mention": "Table 2",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The type of appropriate PPE for each HCW differs depending on the risk level. In this research, HCWs are classified into 3 groups: high risk, medium risk, and low risk (Table 3\n).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Risk Classification of HCWs ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 169,
                    "end": 176,
                    "mention": "Table 3",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The type of PPE needed for each risk group is shown in Table 4\n. According to the US Department of Labor,5 the number of PPE required for HCWs in a high-risk group is 4 sets per day. It is also considered that 2 sets of PPE are required for HCWs in medium- and low-risk groups because HCWs work around 12 hours a day and are required to change PPE every 6 hours during pandemics.20\n",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 105,
                    "end": 106,
                    "mention": "5",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF18"
                },
                {
                    "start": 379,
                    "end": 381,
                    "mention": "20",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF12"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Type and number of PPE required for each HCW per day ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 55,
                    "end": 62,
                    "mention": "Table 4",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The number of gloves depends on how many patients HCWs can treat because gloves should be changed for each patient. We suppose that 20 pairs of gloves/doctor (high risk)/day will be required because 1 SARS report showed that 1 doctor can treat 5 to 10 patients per day from the view of infection control.21\n",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 304,
                    "end": 306,
                    "mention": "21",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF13"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Type and number of PPE required for each HCW per day ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Furthermore, the use of masks by patients is also important to block virus transmission. The US Department of Labor indicates that 1 surgical mask per day is necessary for outpatients and 2 for inpatients.5 All medical and nonmedical workers in the hospital, such as doctors, nurses, medical technologists, pharmacists, caregivers who provide critical care or spiritual care, respiratory therapists, reprocessors of reusable medical devices, and cafeteria workers, in addition to the family members and visitors, also require at least 2 surgical masks per day. The type and number of PPE required for each HCW per day are summarized in Table 5\n.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 205,
                    "end": 206,
                    "mention": "5",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF18"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Type and number of PPE required for each HCW per day ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 636,
                    "end": 643,
                    "mention": "Table 5",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We developed a PPE calculation system based on the following factors: influenza pandemic period of 8 weeks, risk classification by the HCW type, and type and number of PPE required for HCW per day. This system made it possible to demonstrate (1) the average number for each HCW, (2) the required PPE stockpile, and (3) associated expenses from only the location and scale of each hospital. The allocation of doctors and nurses to each risk group is illustrated in Table 3. In this study, we allocated 1/16 of all doctors and nurses to the high-risk group, 3/16 to the medium-risk group, and remaining 3/4 to the low-risk group.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "PPE calculation system ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 464,
                    "end": 471,
                    "mention": "Table 3",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Finally, to give an example, we show the stockpile of PPE required for a sample hospital with 300 beds in Tokyo (Table 6\n). According to this system, the total number of PPE is 10,528 N95 respirators (with exhalation valve), 8848 N95 respirators, 122,192 surgical masks, 21,280 goggles and gowns, 34,832 aprons, and 172,480 pairs of gloves. The total expense for this hospital came to 55,342,000 yen (US $553,420.00; $1=100 yen).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "PPE calculation system ::: Results",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 113,
                    "end": 120,
                    "mention": "Table 6",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In recent years, the government of Japan has appropriated an enormous budget for preventive measures against influenza pandemics, but the major part of this budget is used to stockpile Tamiflu and Relenza and to develop a vaccine.22 Considering that $1 million worth of PPE was required in the first week alone at the beginning of the SARS outbreak in Toronto,23 PPE is as important as infection control measures. It also should be noted that stockpiling a sufficient number of PPE could be a large financial burden on each hospital; however, this must occur before pandemics break out, which will result in a massive shortage of PPE.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 230,
                    "end": 232,
                    "mention": "22",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                },
                {
                    "start": 360,
                    "end": 362,
                    "mention": "23",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Stockpiling PPE at each hospital is a matter of great urgency. The PPE calculation system in this paper will hopefully help to estimate the stockpile of PPE for each hospital. After all, appropriate use of PPE is an essential factor to prevent the transmission of virus. Therefore, the education to HCW should be properly conducted in addition to stockpiling PPE before the pandemic occurs.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
    ],
